{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1805a0ca-c7f9-44b4-8c04-cd7444adc137","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Use `System.IO.Abstractions`** (NuGet package) — it provides `IFileSystem` with `IFile`, `IDirectory`, etc. that mirror the static `System.IO` APIs.\n\n2. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into your classes instead of calling `File.*` / `Directory.*` directly.\n\n3. **In tests**, use the companion package `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers` which gives you `MockFileSystem` — an in-memory file system.\n\n**Before:**\n```csharp\nvar content = File.ReadAllText(path);\n```\n\n**After:**\n```csharp\npublic class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)\n{\n    public string Load(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n```\n\n**In tests:**\n```csharp\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{\\\"key\\\":\\\"value\\\"}\") }\n});\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nAssert.Equal(\"{\\\"key\\\":\\\"value\\\"}\", svc.Load(\"/config.json\"));\n```\n\nThis avoids writing your own wrapper interface and gives you a well-tested, drop-in abstraction for the entire `System.IO` surface.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f765596b-dee8-4d50-a7b7-3c90059f2013","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a design/architecture question about abstracting file system dependencies for testability. Let me provide a concise answer based on best practices.","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"BD1D:2E977A:1F29803:22FF7B6:6A07CAAF"},"id":"a525ea06-175e-4e16-9e44-22e241fac1cb","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:39:06.786Z","parentId":"2fba4b7f-3a9e-4a8f-ac15-62c3c6a8cb94"}
